er Movement of the sixties and seventies. The concluding chapters address the modern day black experience and the images of African Americans in popular culture.Appraising both the existing scholarship and the changing philosophy of the historical profession, this work will be invaluable to scholars, students and general readers alike.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAfrican AmericansxCivil rightszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aCivil rights movementszUnited StatesxHistory. 4aManchester Digital Textbooks. 7aHISTORY / United States / State & Local / General.2bisacsh  aAfrican Americans history.  aBlack Civil Rights.  aBlack Nationalism.  aBlack Power Movement.  aGreat Depression.  aGreat Migration.  aMartin Luther King.  aUS popular culture.  ablack voting rights.  apost-Second World War Civil Rights Movement.  aracial segregation.1 aVerney, Kevern, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb40uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152615373940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526153739423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526153739/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles